"{\"content\":{\"body\":\"**Chapter 1: Vector Analysis**\\n\\n**Problem 1.1: Using the definitions in Eqs. 1.1 and 1.4, and appropriate diagrams,\\\\\\nshow that the dot product and cross product are distributive,\\\\\\na) when the three vectors are co-planar.**\\n\\n**b) in the general case. **\\n\\n**[Solution](https://introductiontoelectrodynamics.blogspot.com/2021/08/problem-1\\\\_27.html)**\\n\\n***\\n\\n**Problem 1.2 Is the cross product associative?**\\n\\n**$$(\\\\vec{A}\\\\times \\\\vec{B}) \\\\times \\\\vec{C} \\\\overset{?}{=} \\\\vec{A}\\\\times (\\\\vec{B} \\\\times \\\\vec{C})$$\\\\\\n**\\n\\n**If so, prove it; if not, provide a counterexample (the simpler the better). [Solution](https://introductiontoelectrodynamics.blogspot.com/2021/08/problem-1\\\\_84.html)**\\n\\n***\\n\\n****Problem 1.3 Find the angle between the body diagonals of a cube. [Solution](https://introductiontoelectrodynamics.blogspot.com/2021/08/problem-1\\\\_31.html)****\\n\\n***\\n\\n******Problem 1.4 Use the cross product to find the components of the unit vector $\\\\hat{n}$\\\\\\nperpendicular to the shaded plane in Fig. 1.11. [Solution](https://introductiontoelectrodynamics.blogspot.com/2021/09/problem-1.html)** ****\\n\\n***\\n\\n**Problem 1.5 Prove the BAC-CAB rule by writing out both sides in component form.**\\n\\n**[Solution](https://introductiontoelectrodynamics.blogspot.com/2021/08/problem-1\\\\_29.html)\\\\\\n**\\n\\n***\\n\\n**Problem 1.6 Prove that**\\n\\n**$$\\\\[\\\\vec{A}\\\\times (\\\\vec{B}\\\\times \\\\vec{C})]+\\\\[\\\\vec{B}\\\\times (\\\\vec{C}\\\\times \\\\vec{A})]+\\\\[\\\\vec{C}\\\\times (\\\\vec{A}\\\\times \\\\vec{B})] = 0$$\\\\\\nUnder what conditions does $\\\\vec{A}\\\\times (\\\\vec{B}\\\\times \\\\vec{C}) = (\\\\vec{A}\\\\times \\\\vec{B})\\\\times \\\\vec{C}$? [Solution](https://introductiontoelectrodynamics.blogspot.com/2021/08/chapter-1-vector-analysis-problem-16.html)**\\n\\n**[Solution](https://introductiontoelectrodynamics.blogspot.com/2021/08/blog-post\\\\_28.html)**\\n\\n***\\n\\n** Problem 1.8**\\n\\n**(a) Prove that the two-dimensional rotation matrix ($\\\\bf Eq. 1.29$) preserves dot products.\\\\\\n(That is, show that $\\\\overline{A_y B_y} + \\\\overline{A_z B_z} = A_y B_y + A_z B_z$ .)\\\\\\n(b) What constraints must the elements ($R\\\\_{i j}$ ) of the three-dimensional rotation matrix\\\\\\n($\\\\bf Eq. 1.30$) satisfy, in order to preserve the length of $\\\\bf{A}$ (for all vectors $\\\\vec{A}$)?**\\n\\n** [Solution](https://introductiontoelectrodynamics.blogspot.com/2021/11/1.html)**\\n\\n***\\n\\n**Problem 1.11 Find the gradients of the following functions:**\\n\\n**(a) $f(x,y,z) = x^2+y^3+z^4$**\\n\\n****(a) $f(x,y,z) = x^2y^3z^4$****\\n\\n******(a) $f(x,y,z) = e^x\\\\sin(y)\\\\ln(z)$ [Solution](https://introductiontoelectrodynamics.blogspot.com/2021/09/1.html)******\\n\\n***\\n\\n********Problem 1.12 The height of a certain hill (in feet) is given by\\\\\\n$$h(x, y) = 10(2xy − 3x^2 − 4y^2 − 18x + 28y + 12),$$\\\\\\nwhere $y$ is the distance (in miles) north, $x$ the distance east of South Hadley.\\\\\\n(a) Where is the top of the hill located?\\\\\\n(b) How high is the hill?\\\\\\n(c) How steep is the slope (in feet per mile) at a point 1 mile north and one mile\\\\\\neast of South Hadley? In what direction is the slope steepest, at that point?********\\n\\n********[Solution](https://introductiontoelectrodynamics.blogspot.com/2021/09/problem-1\\\\_3.html) **\\\\\\n******\\n\\n***\\n\\n**[![](https://1.bp.blogspot.com/-xII1Fx7gqs0/YTIDgUKS9CI/AAAAAAAAG\\\\_4/bfvyfe7-paIKGNV-ciQZ_OkcgyupLyWbwCLcBGAsYHQ/s16000/Screenshot%2B2021-09-03%2Bat%2B16-42-51%2BPost%2BEdit.png)](https://1.bp.blogspot.com/-xII1Fx7gqs0/YTIDgUKS9CI/AAAAAAAAG\\\\_4/bfvyfe7-paIKGNV-ciQZ_OkcgyupLyWbwCLcBGAsYHQ/s576/Screenshot%2B2021-09-03%2Bat%2B16-42-51%2BPost%2BEdit.png)**\\n\\n**[Solution](https://introductiontoelectrodynamics.blogspot.com/2021/09/chapter-1-vector-analysis-problem-113.html)**\\n\\n***\\n\\n**Problem 1.15 Calculate the divergence of the following vector functions:**\\n\\n**(a) $v_a = x^2\\\\hat{i}+3xz^2\\\\hat{j}-2xz\\\\hat{k}$**\\n\\n****(b) $v_b = xy\\\\hat{i}+2yz\\\\hat{j}+3zx\\\\hat{k}$****\\n\\n******(c) $v_c = y^2\\\\hat{i}+(2xy+z^2)\\\\hat{j}+2yz\\\\hat{k}$******\\n\\n** [Solution](https://introductiontoelectrodynamics.blogspot.com/2021/09/problem-1\\\\_4.html)**\\n\\n***\\n\\n**Problem 1.16 Sketch the vector function**\\n\\n**$$\\\\vec{v} = \\\\frac{\\\\hat{r}}{r^2}$$**\\n\\n**and compute its divergence. The answer may surprise you.. can you explain it?**\\n\\n** [Solution](https://introductiontoelectrodynamics.blogspot.com/2021/09/problem-1\\\\_21.html)**\\n\\n***\\n\\n**Calculate CURL of vector in different coordinate system? [Article](https://introductiontoelectrodynamics.blogspot.com/2021/11/calculate-curl-in-different-coordinate.html)**\\n\\n***\\n\\n**Problem 1.18 Calculate the CURL of the following vector functions:**\\n\\n**(a) $v_a = x^2\\\\hat{i}+3xz^2\\\\hat{j}-2xz\\\\hat{k}$**\\n\\n****(b) $v_b = xy\\\\hat{i}+2yz\\\\hat{j}+3zx\\\\hat{k}$****\\n\\n******(c) $v_c = y^2\\\\hat{i}+(2xy+z^2)\\\\hat{j}+2yz\\\\hat{k}$******\\n\\n** [Solution](https://introductiontoelectrodynamics.blogspot.com/2021/11/problem-1.html)**\\n\\n***\\n\\n**Problem 1.27: Prove that the divergence of a curl is always zero. Check it for function\\\\\\n$v_a$ in Prob. 1.15. ($v_a = x^2\\\\hat{x} + 3xz^2\\\\hat{y} - 2xz\\\\hat{z}$). [Solution](https://introductiontoelectrodynamics.blogspot.com/2021/08/blog-post.html) **\\n\\n****\\n\\n***\\n\\n** Problem 1.54: Check the divergence theorem for the function\\\\\\n$$v = r^2\\\\cos\\\\theta\\\\hat{r} + r^2\\\\cos \\\\phi \\\\hat{θ} − r^2 \\\\cos\\\\theta \\\\sin \\\\phi \\\\hat{\\\\phi}$$ ,\\\\\\nusing as your volume one octant of the sphere of radius $R$ (Fig. 1.48). Make sure\\\\\\nyou include the entire surface. [Solution](https://introductiontoelectrodynamics.blogspot.com/2021/08/chapter-1-problem-154.html) **\\n\\n[]()****\\n\\n***\\n\\n** **Problem 1.55: Check Stokes’ theorem using the function $v = ay\\\\vec{x} + bx \\\\vec{y}$ ($a$ and $b$ are constants) and the circular path of radius $R$, centered at the origin in the $xy$ plane. [Solution](https://introductiontoelectrodynamics.blogspot.com/2021/08/chapter-1-problem-155.html)***** **\\n\\n<!--more-->\\n\\n** **Problem 1.56: Compute the line integral of\\\\\\n$$v = 6 \\\\hat{x} + yz^2 \\\\hat{y} + (3y + z) \\\\hat{z}$$\\\\\\nalong the triangular path shown in Fig. 1.49. Check your answer using Stokes’\\\\\\ntheorem.[Solution](https://introductiontoelectrodynamics.blogspot.com/2021/08/problem-1.html)****\\n\\n***\\n\\n** **\\n\\n<!--more-->\\n\\n** Chapter 2: Electrostatics **\\n\\n****Problem 2.10: A charge $q$ sits at the back corner of a cube, as shown in Fig. 2.17.\\\\\\nWhat is the flux of E through the shaded side? [Solution](https://introductiontoelectrodynamics.blogspot.com/2021/08/problem-2.html)****\\n\\n***\\n\\n<!--more-->\\n\\n** **Problem 2.11: Use Gauss’s law to find the electric field inside and outside a spherical\\\\\\nshell of radius R that carries a uniform surface charge density σ. Compare your\\\\\\nanswer to Prob. 2.7. [Solution](https://introductiontoelectrodynamics.blogspot.com/2021/08/chapter-1-electrostatics-problem-211.html)****\\n\\n***\\n\\n** **\\n\\n<!--more-->\\n\\n** **Problem 2.12 Use Gauss’s law to find the electric field inside a uniformly charged\\\\\\nsolid sphere (charge density $\\\\rho$). Compare your answer to Prob. 2.8. [Solution](https://introductiontoelectrodynamics.blogspot.com/2021/08/chapter-2-electrostatics-problem-212.html)****\\n\\n***\\n\\n** **\\n\\n<!--more-->\\n\\n** **Problem 2.13: Find the electric field a distance s from an infinitely long straight\\\\\\nwire that carries a uniform line charge $\\\\lambda$. Compare Eq. 2.9. [Solution](https://introductiontoelectrodynamics.blogspot.com/2021/08/chapter-2-electrostatics-problem-213.html)****\\n\\n***\\n\\n** **\\n\\n<!--more-->\\n\\n** **Problem 2.14 Find the electric field inside a sphere that carries a charge density proportional to the distance from the origin, $ρ = kr$, for some constant $k$. \\\\[Hint: This charge density is not uniform, and you must integrate to get the enclosed charge.] [Solution](https://introductiontoelectrodynamics.blogspot.com/2021/08/2.html)****\\n\\n***\\n\\n** **\\n\\n<!--more-->\\n\\n** **Problem 2.38: A metal sphere of radius $R$, carrying charge $q$, is surrounded by a\\\\\\nthick concentric metal shell (inner radius $a$, outer radius $b$, as in Fig. 2.48). The\\\\\\nshell carries no net charge.\\\\\\n(a) Find the surface charge density $\\\\sigma$ at $R$, at $a$, and at $b$.\\\\\\n(b) Find the potential at the center, using infinity as the reference point.\\\\\\n(c) Now the outer surface is touched to a grounding wire, which drains off charge\\\\\\nand lowers its potential to zero (same as at infinity). How do your answers to\\\\\\n(a) and (b) change? [Solution](https://introductiontoelectrodynamics.blogspot.com/2021/08/problem-2\\\\_26.html)****\\n\\n<!--more-->\\n\",\"timestamp\":1637751933,\"title\":\"List of Questions and link to solutions\"},\"digest\":\"-268l5paWsiV_ykSj9gaqKXsO2L94eP_VD2E1aVW4rg\",\"authorship\":{\"contributor\":\"0x7Df3447e3b00A0d23d805e1908742a23e7B962E6\",\"signingKey\":\"{\\\"crv\\\":\\\"P-256\\\",\\\"ext\\\":true,\\\"key_ops\\\":[\\\"verify\\\"],\\\"kty\\\":\\\"EC\\\",\\\"x\\\":\\\"nafb_u7dqMj9zJ4hW1F2c0h-qE3FmVllJmd1x7E6t6c\\\",\\\"y\\\":\\\"BtUpCIRrgG-264CDyasgGUCinunspmIUQU6aw3RIdoo\\\"}\",\"signature\":\"9B__acwhbSe1Yt4J2kbewNF2cdHwCI_hnHc2v7BRn3ZwXsG8u4L5HUWT3SRCAUothwWKpIc_84joNoVnVKwydw\",\"signingKeySignature\":\"0x3e3bc254c54edb63931da57c50986bc5411c1df57b2755cfc5c23f7c1448698045ea61b3eebf576cb41ef26236bbab2b47a866a6612d5901a562c52d5238d4811c\",\"signingKeyMessage\":\"I authorize publishing on mirror.xyz from this device using:\\n{\\\"crv\\\":\\\"P-256\\\",\\\"ext\\\":true,\\\"key_ops\\\":[\\\"verify\\\"],\\\"kty\\\":\\\"EC\\\",\\\"x\\\":\\\"nafb_u7dqMj9zJ4hW1F2c0h-qE3FmVllJmd1x7E6t6c\\\",\\\"y\\\":\\\"BtUpCIRrgG-264CDyasgGUCinunspmIUQU6aw3RIdoo\\\"}\",\"algorithm\":{\"name\":\"ECDSA\",\"hash\":\"SHA-256\"}},\"nft\":{},\"version\":\"12-21-2020\",\"originalDigest\":\"-268l5paWsiV_ykSj9gaqKXsO2L94eP_VD2E1aVW4rg\"}"